ABOUT SSBCI

State Small Business Credit Initiative

In 2020, the US Treasury renewed SSBCI 2.0 with a $10B budget. The program is administered by States, DC, territories, and Tribal governments. This includes venture capital programs, loan participation programs, loan guarantee programs, collateral support programs, and capital access programs. Funds are released in tranches based on demonstrated outcomes.

  • US Treasury allocates funds based on State population, Tribal allocations separately.
  • SSBCI allocates funds for Venture Capital programs in a supplemental form to existing capital, requires proof of impact.
  • Program requires fund compliance and reporting on job creation, underserved communities, and fund dispersion.



Open States & Funds for Venture Capital

Arizona $87 million
Seed and Series A-stage focused venture funds and early-stage technology startups.
Connecticut
The Connecticut Future Fund for underserved & diverse founders of small businesses; The ClimateTech (CT) Fund supporting early-stage businesses with a focus on clean energy, environmentally safe manufacturing, and climate resiliency.
Indiana $70 million
Targets seed- to early-stage investments in Indiana innovators and startups seeking between $500,000 and $5 million in equity capital financing.
Maine $20 million
Targets startups with fewer than 10 employees in a state largely underserved by venture capital investors.
New Hampshire
$61.5 million across 5 different lending and venture programs.
Pennsylvania $142 million
Provide direct equity investments in seed and early-stage technology companies in Pennsylvania through longstanding partners Ben Franklin Technology Partners and Life Sciences Greenhouses, as well as venture capital investments in new funds under the management of underserved venture capital firms.
South Carolina $51 million
Expand access to capital for underserved communities by leveraging relationships with partner organizations.
Michigan
Approved for $236 million across lending and venture capital programs.
West Virginia
$72 million total funding across lending and venture capital. Seed capital co-investment fund with more than half of its allocation.
South Dakota
No venture capital program.
Vermont $29 million
Seed fund investments, investments leveraging accelerator programs to make small investments in rural, pre-seed stage companies, and investments in high-growth, technology innovation companies in the healthcare sector.
